Number of Instances*
Number of Instances
This is the number of virtual machines you want to create.
Learn more about Compute Engine pricing
Instance-time*
Compute time
The compute time is the total amount of time that your virtual machines are running in a given month. For example, if you have 1 virtual machine running the entire month, then the compute time would be 730 hours (365 days * 24 hours per day divided by 12 months). If you have 10 instances also running all the time, then the compute time would be 730 * 10 = 7300 hours.
Learn more about the instance uptime billing model
Changing Instance-time will automatically calculate number of instances, assuming 100% run time.
Changing Instance-time will automatically calculate number of instances, assuming 100% run time.

Instances using ephemeral public IP
Instances using ephemeral public IP
Ephemeral public IP addresses are public IP addresses that are assigned to a VM when it is created and are released when the VM is deleted. If you only need to access your VM from within your VPC, you can set this field to '0'. If you need to access your VM from outside of your VPC, you can specify the number of ephemeral public IP addresses that you need.
Learn more about ephemeral public IP pricing

Must be less than or equal to the number of instances
Instances using static public IP
Instances using static public IP
Static public IP addresses are public IP addresses that are assigned to a VM when it is created and remain reserved even after the VM is deleted. If you only need to access your VM from within your VPC, you can set this field to '0'. If you need to access your VM from outside of your VPC, you can specify the number of ephemeral public IP addresses that you need.
Learn more about static public IP pricing

Must be less than or equal to the number of instances

Provisioning Model
Provisioning Model
The availability of the virtual machines you want to create. You can choose Regular Virtual Machines, or Spot (Preemptible VMs). Regular VMs have a higher cost hourly rate and they are available 24/7, giving you full control of when to start and stop it. Spot VMs on the other hand have a lower cost hourly rate and are self-preempted, which means they are stopped at any point within 24 hours after being started.
Learn more about Spot VMs
Machine type
Machine type
The machine type specifies machine series, the family and number of CPUs, and amount of memory for your Compute Engine instances. For example, a 'n1-standard-4' machine, is of the N1 series, General Purpose family, has 4 vCPU, and 15 GB of memory.
Learn more about machine type pricing
Machine FamilyGeneral Purpose
  • General PurposeBest price-performance for general workloads.
  • Compute-optimizedHighest performance per core for compute-intensive workloads.
  • Memory-optimizedIdeal for memory-intensive workloads, up to 12 TB of memory.
  • Accelerator-optimizedIdeal for massively parallelized CUDA compute workloads, such as ML and HPC.

  • T2ABest per-core performance/cost for scale-out workloads
  • T2DBest per-core performance/cost for scale-out workloads
  • C3Consistently high performance
  • C3DConsistently high performance

Extended memory
Extended memory
Extended memory is a feature that allows you to increase the amount of memory available to your VM beyond the standard amount, up to 624GB or 768GB depending on the machine series. This can be useful if you need to run memory-intensive applications or if you need to store large amounts of data in memory.
Learn more about extended memory

Threads per core
Threads per core
The number of threads per core determines how many concurrent tasks can be run on a single core. For example, if you have a 2-core CPU and you set this number to 2, you can run up to 4 concurrent tasks on the CPU. Configuring the number of threads(vCPU) per core is useful in helping to reduce costs with licensing, where license costs are based on the number of vCPU used. Reducing the number of threads per core can impact your performance.
Learn more about setting threads per core
Boot disk type
Boot disk type
Each Compute Engine VM has a single boot disk that contains the operating system and file system. Each boot disk type has a unique price and performance characteristics. Standard is the most cost-effective, and SSD the one with the highest performance.
Learn more about persistent disk types
Boot disk size (GiB)
Boot disk size (GiB)
The size of the boot disk should be large enough to accommodate your operating system and any applications you plan to install. For example, a Linux distribution such as Ubuntu typically requires around 20GiB of disk space.
Learn more about disk pricing
Enable Confidential VM service
Confidential VM service
A Confidential VM is a type of VM that ensures that your data and applications stay private and encrypted even while in use. You should use Confidential VMs to limit the risk of exposing sensitive data and workloads during processing.
Learn more about Confidential VMs

Confidential VM Service is only available for the N2D, and C2D machine series
Add sustained use discounts
Sustained use discounts
Sustained use discounts(SUDs) are discounts automatically applied to your instances based on your usage of them in a given month. If you expect to use your VM for more than 28 days, you can add sustained use discounts to save money.
Learn more about sustained use discounts
Add GPUs
GPUs
GPUs can accelerate your workloads. They are specifically designed to improve machine learning, and graphics-intensive workloads. You can add GPUs to your machine by selecting the number of GPUs and the type of GPU you want to use.
Learn more about GPUs on Compute Engine

GPUs are only available for N1, G2, and A2 machine series
